It is difficult to believe that Dante can have written such a sentence as the MS. reading here (⁴ cum sit uobis principium ciuilitatis esse ipsu'm quoque ⁹), which is moreover impossible from the point of view of the cursus, It is no doubt a case of ‘pie '‚ as to which see Moore, Studies in Dante, iv. 6, 33. Moore shows how easily a confused sentence like the above may arise—words acci- dentally omitted by a primitive copyist, and by him (or another) written in the margin, subsequently get inserted in the text, but in the wrong place. 'The process is analogous to that by which marginal glosses become embodied in the text. The omission of

’ civilitatis (which apparently was caught by the copyist from the preceding line), and the substitution of ipsius for ipsum, are due to Witte. It may be noted that the phrase ipsius esse, in the genitive, occurs in Epist. x. 398.
